Doctor Natalie Rasgon, professor of psychiatry and behavioural sciences at the Stanford University School of Medicine, said: 'ApoE4 is contributing to ageing at the cellular level well before any outward symptoms of decline become apparent.

'Yet, oestrogen [found in HRT] appears to have a protective effect for middle-aged women who are carrying this genetic risk factor.'

Numerous previous studies have suggested that ApoE4 contributes to age-related mental decline and Alzheimer’s disease.

The gene variant is present in about 40 per cent of people with late-onset Alzheimer’s.

Prof Rasgon’s team focused on telomeres - caps on the ends of chromosomes that keep DNA stable and act like genetic fuses.

Every time a cell divides, its telomeres shorten.

